      <p class="key-stat-txt">After ingestion, L-theanine crosses the blood-brain barrier and increases <strong>alpha brain wave activity</strong> — the same brain state associated with meditation, flow, and calm focus. Documented in <em>Nutritional Neuroscience</em>, 2008.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The mechanism is elegant in its simplicity: L-theanine increases GABA (the brain's primary calming neurotransmitter), serotonin, and dopamine levels while simultaneously reducing excitatory glutamate signaling. This rebalances the excitatory-to-inhibitory neurotransmitter ratio without sedation — producing what EEG studies show as a marked increase in alpha-1 and alpha-2 wave activity in the occipital and parietal brain regions.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
